In <strnlghtC7Hr78.JnH@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>In article <WCS.93May20202241@rainier.ATT.COM> wcs@anchor.ho.att.com (Bill
>Stewart +1-908-949-0705) writes:


>>	  There is such legislation.  It's in the Arms Control Act.  I have
>>   looked this up.  Look in the index to the USC under Arms Control.
>>   [....]  The general export control system is administered
>>   by the Commerce Department, and, while a pain, can be dealt with.  There's 
>>   a separate system for "arms control", administered by State and Defense.
>>   This controls the import and export of items listed on the "Munitions List".
>>   The Munitions List (which is a real list, published in the Code of
>>   Federal Regulations) lists all the items for which "arms control" applies.
>>   Items like "battleships" and "rifles" appear.  Unfortunately, so does
>>   "cryptographic equipment", because, when the Munitions List was created
>>   decades ago, civilian cryptography barely existed.  Cryptographic
>>   equipment is the only "dual use" technology covered under arms control,
>>   and NSA has lobbied strongly to keep it that way.
>>
>>However, what constitutes "equipment"?  Is software "equipment",
>>or only hardware?  Some of the rules have export restrictions on
>>equipment and "technical data", but import restrictions only on equipment.
>>(Does software become hardware if you store it on magnetic media
>>and physically ship the media?)  The rules for technical data also
>>appear to be different for publicly available data.
>>

>You should read the regs. Jim Bidzos once quoted them to me (unfortunately I
>lost the message). It specifies software, flow charts, etc. for
>cryptography. It was pretty loophole-free, as I recall my reading of it.

You may be correct, although Jim Bidzos may be selectively quoting. 
However, the law includes "software" under "technical data", which may be
freely imported; hence, if Jim is correct, the regs are not compatible with
the law.
